# ndi-no-video-incident — OBS shows black cameras while NDI is healthy (live incident log)
#
# status: OPEN. fault isolated to the OBS NDI RECEIVER (discovery). cameras,
# network, RTSP, the RTSP->NDI converter, and the NDI runtime are all PROVEN
# healthy. see companion [[streamlabs-cameras]], [[ip-cameras]], [[powershell]].
#
# the rig (as understood):
#   cameras (RTSP, static IPs)  ->  [ RTSP->NDI converter ]  ->  NDI  ->  OBS
#     Left   10.0.220.51 :554 /stream1   (switch port 5)
#     Center 10.0.220.52 :554 /stream1   (switch port 7)
#     Right  10.0.220.53 :554 /stream1   (switch port 6)
#   StreamMachine (Windows 10, runs OBS):
#     NIC A 172.16.23.37  (switch port 2)  <- internet/control, holds default gw
#     NIC B 10.0.220.24   (switch port 3, mac f6:77)  <- camera LAN
#   symptom: OBS cameras black; graphics-PC PiP works; rebooting PC + cameras
#   3x changed nothing.


WHAT WE PROVED HEALTHY (elimination ladder)
-------------------------------------------

# all of these PASSED, so each layer is exonerated.

# from carl (Linux, on a subnet ROUTED to the camera LAN):
#   (1) ping -c4 10.0.220.51/52/53        -> all reply, ttl=63 (1 router hop)
#   (2) nc -vz -w 3 10.0.220.5x 554       -> all "succeeded!" (RTSP port open)
#   (3) ffprobe -rtsp_transport tcp \
#         rtsp://10.0.220.51:554/stream1  -> valid stream: H.264 Main,
#                                            1920x1080, 30fps, + AAC stereo.
#                                            NO creds required, /stream1 correct.
#   => cameras, switch, camera LAN, RTSP all healthy. (VLC failed to open the
#      MRL — a VLC 3.0.x quirk with forced-TCP + SDP c=IN IP4 0.0.0.0, NOT a
#      camera fault; ffprobe/ffplay/mpv read it fine.)
#   CAVEAT: carl ROUTES to 10.0.220.x, so this proves the cameras, not the
#   StreamMachine's path. (see below — NDI rendered that moot anyway.)

# on the StreamMachine itself (same Windows box as OBS):
#   (4) NDI Studio Monitor -> shows live video for ALL THREE cameras.
#   => on the OBS box: cameras + RTSP->NDI converter + NDI discovery + NDI data
#      path + the NICs are ALL working. nothing outside OBS is at fault.
#      the dual-NIC / wrong-subnet theory is DEAD for this incident.


WHERE THE FAULT IS
------------------

# Studio Monitor (uses the system NDI RUNTIME) finds + renders all 3.
# OBS (uses its own NDI PLUGIN = DistroAV / obs-ndi, a SEPARATE NDI finder)
# does NOT find the cameras by name. => the fault is the OBS NDI RECEIVER's
# DISCOVERY, on the same machine where Studio Monitor works fine.


OPEN SUSPECTS / NEXT STEPS (resume here)
----------------------------------------

# in order of likelihood for "Studio Monitor sees them, OBS finds nothing":

# (A) OBS NDI plugin not loaded / version mismatch with the NDI runtime.
#     - OBS -> Tools menu: is there an NDI / DistroAV entry? if NOT, the plugin
#       didn't load -> that alone explains an empty dropdown.
#     - Help -> Log Files -> View Current Log: grep for "NDI" (logs runtime
#       version found, or load error).
#     - fix: reinstall the OBS NDI plugin and let it install ITS bundled NDI
#       runtime version (NDI 5 vs NDI 6 mismatch is the classic cause).

# (B) Windows Firewall blocking obs64.exe discovery (per-APP rules).
#     - the camera NIC may be on the "Public" firewall profile.
#     - Defender Firewall -> Allow an app -> obs64.exe checked for Domain,
#       Private, AND Public.

# (C) NDI Access Manager -> Receive tab: enable the group the converter uses
#     (default "Public"); or set a Discovery Server to bypass flaky mDNS.

# (D) plain restart of OBS to force a discovery re-scan (cheap, try first).

# if OBS DOES list the names but feed is still black: stale source name
# (re-select in the source Properties dropdown), wrong scene, hidden (eye),
# broken Transform (-> Fit to Screen), or z-order. (this turned out NOT to be
# the case — OBS isn't finding them by name at all.)


LIVE WORKAROUNDS (to air video without fixing OBS NDI)
------------------------------------------------------

# (1) WINDOW CAPTURE of NDI Studio Monitor  <- used during this incident.
#     Studio Monitor already renders all 3 on the OBS box. In OBS add a
#     Window Capture source targeting the Studio Monitor window (run 3
#     monitors, one per camera, or one + crop). bypasses the NDI plugin
#     entirely. guaranteed to work since Studio Monitor is proven working.
#
# (2) MEDIA SOURCE straight to RTSP (bypass NDI):
#       add Media Source -> uncheck Local File -> Input =
#       rtsp://USER:PASS@10.0.220.51:554/stream1, Input Format rtsp,
#       Input Args -rtsp_transport tcp ...   (see [[streamlabs-cameras]])
#     CAVEAT: requires the StreamMachine itself to reach 10.0.220.x directly
#     (NIC B). Studio Monitor proves NDI arrives, NOT that OBS can route RTSP
#     to the cameras — if the converter is a different box, this may fail.
#     window-capture (1) is the safer instant save.


